[3]
Date: Sat 9 Aug 2008
From: David Quammen <quammen@imt.net>


With all due respect, I must say that I think you've got some wildly
misleading numbers and calculations in your moderator's note to the
posting (below) about anthrax on the Flying D Ranch.

First of all, Mod.MHJ states that the ranch is 13 343 acres in area.
My information (from several sources, including a recent tour of the
ranch) says that it's 100 000 acres bigger than that, namely 113 000
acres. I think you missed by an order of magnitude. Probably a
misplaced decimal point.

Secondly, Mod.MHJ then reports that, with 4000 bison on the ranch,
that translates to 3.3 animals per acre, "which density may well go
to explain the increasing number of animals affected." Wrong again:
There is no such density. Even the figures you report would translate
to 3.3 acres per animal, not 3.3 animals per acre.

Finally, if you use the correct size of the ranch (113 000 acres) and
the stated number of bison (4000), that amounts to a rather low
density, allowing 28 acres per animal.

Am I missing something? If not, I think you should be a bit more
careful about propagating the impression that the ranch is suffering
relatively severe anthrax mortality because it is overstocked.

(I live here, but I'm unaffiliated with Turner Enterprises.)

--
David Quammen
Bozeman, MT
<quammen@imt.net>

[Mea culpa. The moral of this is not to post anything when harried
and under an onrushing deadline to do something else.

Originally, I was told that this ranch had 18 000 acres, and checking
the map <http://www.tedturner.com/returner/turner_ranch_map_web.jpg>,
the nearest ranch with bison was the Snowcrest with 13 343 acres; the
Bar None Ranch with 22 129 acres has only elk. Mistake 1: I missed
the early report (20080805.2405 and then 20080808.2442) naming the
Flying D Ranch with 113 613 acres. Mistake 2: I switched animals for
acres. And, unfortunately, though it was caught internally, it was
after posting. Mistakes happen. I am sorry.

It is fortunate that we moderators don't screw up more often than we
do and then in front of a global audience. Still, if one is going to
do so, what better than to have a biggy so it is obvious? - Mod.MHJ]
